# KVL

![[../60-Meta-Attachments/1dc050ca900570088462e874f6ca59db.png|../60-Meta-Attachments/1dc050ca900570088462e874f6ca59db.png]]

> [!word] Kirchoff's Voltage Law
> Sum of all [[61-Archive/20220411113721-circuit-branches|branch]] [[61-Archive/20220318120826-voltage|voltages]] in a closed loop should be 0 at all times.

$$
V= V_1+V_2
$$

- The reason for why KVL stands is because voltage are spread in series (See [[61-Archive/20220411105450-resistor-in-series|Resistor in Series]])

## Method

1. Count the nodes and define all [[61-Archive/20220408104411-current|current]] directions (one [[61-Archive/20220411113840-node|node]] can be
   designated as GND and ignored)
2. Write the [[61-Archive/20220411113840-node|node]] equations
   a. Node 1: $I=I_3+I_1$
   b. Node 2: $I_1=I_2$
3. Choose one [[61-Archive/20220411113840-node|node]] to express branch [[61-Archive/20220408104411-current|current]] using [[61-Archive/20220411113840-node|node]] [[61-Archive/20220318120826-voltage|voltage]]
   Node 1: $I=I_3+I_1=\frac{V}{R_3}+ \frac{V}{R_1+R_2}$

- Free to assign any direction of [[61-Archive/20220408104411-current|current]]

## Example

> [[../60-Meta-Attachments/d1ea8c695932d8c3c9bde23ee6d7045a.png|!example]]
> Loop 1: $V_{13}-V=0$
> Loop 2: $V_{12}+V_{23}+V_{31}=0$
> Loop 3: $V_{12}+V_{23}-V=0$
